            <a:r>
              <a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/>
              <a:t>Importance decay elegantly solves the &quot;old facts rank same as new facts&quot; problem. The formula is dead simple: effective_importance = importance times (decay_rate to the power of days). Profile stuff decays slowly — 0.998 per day, so it's still relevant after three months. Task state decays faster — 0.95 per day, so it fades in two weeks. Postgres does the math inline with POWER() so you're not looping through code. Confidence filtering is already there in the schema, we just need to use it during selection. Drop anything below 0.4 confidence, tag 0.4-0.6 with [uncertain] so agents know to verify. Pretty straightforward safety improvement.</a:t>
            </a:r>
          </a:p>
        </p:txBody>
